{"key":"post-17834545","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>17834545</id>\n<content>It's interesting how this type of thread gets repeated every few years.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;One can use plastic sheeting with pin holes all over it, crinkled up wax paper, crinkled up parchment paper, etc., and grow without even using a fruiting chamber. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Bubble wrap fits this genera too, since it holds a micro-climate right at the surface of the substrate.&amp;nbsp; There are lots of materials that could be used including the old standard wax paper, a piece of sheet metal, cardboard, the plastic lids that come with Glad baking trays, etc., etc.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The idea is to hold a microclimate right at the surface of the substrate which holds humidity but still allows fresh air to penetrate, which scrubs off the stale air.&amp;nbsp; These are the conditions which are conducive to pinset formation and the number of materials one can use to accomplish the above are limitless.&amp;nbsp; I'm not sure each individual material requires a new 'tek' as they are all doing the same thing; providing a micro-climate at the surface of the substrate. &lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>17834557</next>\n<prev>17834479</prev>\n<first>17788866</first>\n<last>17854139</last>\n<when>1361371797</when>\n<utime>02/20/13 04:49 PM</utime>\n</post>"}